    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-07-29T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-07-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="363"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d363">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">862.20291/16</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by the Assistant Chief of the
                        Division of Near Eastern Affairs</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Alling</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-07-29">July 29,
                            1941</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <table>
                    <row>
                        <cell rendition="#nowrap #top">Participants:</cell>
                        <cell rendition="#hanging">Mr. Nevile Butler, Minister-Counselor of British
                            Embassy.</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell rendition="#hanging">Mr. Murray<note n="63" xml:id="d363fn63">Wallace
                                Murray, Chief of the Division of Near Eastern Affairs.</note>
                        </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell rendition="#hanging">Mr. Alling</cell>
                    </row>
                </table>
                <p>Mr. Butler said that a few days ago Mr. Maisky, the Soviet Ambassador at London,
                    suggested to Mr. Eden<note n="64" xml:id="d363fn64">Anthony Eden, British
                        Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs.</note> that the British and Soviet
                    Governments make joint representations to the Iranian Government urging it to
                    get rid of between 5,000 and 10,000 German agents operating in Iran. Mr. Butler
                    said that Mr. Eden had agreed to this proposal and that the joint
                    representations had been made in Tehran a day or two ago. He said that the
                    Iranian reply was noncommittal.</p>
            </div>
